#. HTML: </p><h1>
#. VAR: 36. Jhānasutta → jhānanissayasuttaṃ (bj)
msgctxt "an9.36:0.3"
msgid "36. Jhānasutta "
msgstr "36. Depending on Absorption "

#. HTML: </h1></div><p>
#. REF: sc1
msgctxt "an9.36:1.1"
msgid "“Paṭhamampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, jhānaṃ nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "“Mendicants, I say that the first absorption is a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.2"
msgid "dutiyampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, jhānaṃ nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The second absorption is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.3"
msgid "tatiyampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, jhānaṃ nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The third absorption is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.4"
msgid "catutthampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, jhānaṃ nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The fourth absorption is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.5"
msgid "ākāsānañcāyatanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The dimension of infinite space is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.6"
msgid "viññāṇañcāyatanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The dimension of infinite consciousness is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.7"
msgid "ākiñcaññāyatanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The dimension of nothingness is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.8"
msgid "nevasaññānāsaññāyatanampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi; "
msgstr "The dimension of neither perception nor non-perception is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:1.9"
msgid "saññāvedayitanirodhampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmi. "
msgstr "The cessation of perception and feeling is also a basis for ending the defilements. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-vp-pli4.423, sc2
msgctxt "an9.36:2.1"
msgid "‘Paṭhamampāhaṃ, bhikkhave, jhānaṃ nissāya āsavānaṃ khayaṃ vadāmī’ti, iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ. "
msgstr "‘The first absorption is a basis for ending the defilements.’ "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.2"
msgid "Kiñcetaṃ paṭicca vuttaṃ? "
msgstr "That’s what I said, but why did I say it? "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.3"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati. "
msgstr "Take a mendicant who, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption. "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.4"
msgid "So yadeva tattha hoti rūpagataṃ vedanāgataṃ saññāgataṃ saṅkhāragataṃ viññāṇagataṃ, te dhamme aniccato dukkhato rogato gaṇḍato sallato aghato ābādhato parato palokato suññato anattato samanupassati. "
msgstr "They contemplate the phenomena there—included in form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness—as impermanent, as suffering, as diseased, as an abscess, as a dart, as misery, as an affliction, as alien, as falling apart, as empty, as not-self. "

#. VAR: paṭivāpeti → patiṭṭhāpeti (s1-3) | paṭipādeti (mr)
msgctxt "an9.36:2.5"
msgid "So tehi dhammehi cittaṃ paṭivāpeti. "
msgstr "They turn their mind away from those things, "

#. VAR: paṭivāpetvā → patiṭṭhāpetvā (s1-3) | paṭipādetvā (mr)
msgctxt "an9.36:2.6"
msgid "So tehi dhammehi cittaṃ paṭivāpetvā amatāya dhātuyā cittaṃ upasaṃharati: "
msgstr "and apply it to the deathless: "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.7"
msgid "‘etaṃ santaṃ etaṃ paṇītaṃ yadidaṃ sabbasaṅkhārasamatho sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nirodho nibbānan’ti. "
msgstr "‘This is peaceful; this is sublime—that is, the stilling of all activities, the letting go of all attachments, the ending of craving, fading away, cessation, extinguishment.’ "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.8"
msgid "So tattha ṭhito āsavānaṃ khayaṃ pāpuṇāti. "
msgstr "Abiding in that they attain the ending of defilements. "

msgctxt "an9.36:2.9"
msgid "No ce āsavānaṃ khayaṃ pāpuṇāti, teneva dhammarāgena tāya dhammanandiyā pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko hoti tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā. "
msgstr "If they don’t attain the ending of defilements, with the ending of the five lower fetters they’re reborn spontaneously, because of their passion and love for that meditation. They are extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world. "

